The '''1994 [[Commonwealth Games]]''' were held in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], in the province of [[British Columbia]] in Canada, from 18 to 28 August 1994.

The XV Commonwealth Games ([[French language|French]]: ''XV<sup>éme</sup> Jeux du Commonwealth'') marked [[South Africa]]'s return to the Commonwealth Games following the [[apartheid]] era, and over 30 years since the country last competed in the [[1958 Commonwealth Games|Games in 1958]]. [[Namibia]] participated in its first Games after gaining independence from South Africa in 1990, and the Caribbean island of [[Montserrat]] also made their Games debut. It was also [[Hong Kong]]'s last appearance at the Games before the [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|transfer of sovereignty]] from Britain to [[China]].

The official mascot of the Games was an [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[killer whale]] named "Klee Wyck".<ref>http://www.umanitoba.ca/cm/cmarchive/vol21no6/revkleewyck.html</ref> "Klee Wyck", meaning "the laughing one", was a nickname given to Canadian painter and sculptor [[Emily Carr]] by the [[Ucluelet First Nation]].<ref>http://bcheritage.ca/emilycarrhomework/writing/klee.htm</ref>

Ten types of sports were featured at the Victoria Games: athletics, [[Aquatic sports|aquatics]], badminton, [[boxing]], cycling, gymnastics, [[Lawn bowling|lawn bowls]], shooting, [[Powerlifting|weightlifting]], and [[wrestling]].

==Host selection==
Three bids for the 1994 Commonwealth Games were submitted. Victoria, New Delhi, and Cardiff were the bidding cities. On 15 September 1988, the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] voted to award Victoria the 1994 Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Victoria wins 1994 Games|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19880916&id=0a1UAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GJADAAAAIBAJ&pg=3003,139394&hl=en|publisher=''[[New Straits Times]]''|date=16 September 1988|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref>

