{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}

[[File:Basketball net.jpg|thumb|Typical professional hoop with backboard]]
[[File:BasketballHoop.jpg|thumb|Typical privately owned basketball hoop with backboard]]
A '''backboard''' is a piece of [[basketball]] equipment. It is a raised vertical board with an attached '''basket''' consisting of a net suspended from a hoop. It is made of a flat, rigid piece of, often [[Plexiglas]] or [[toughened glass|tempered glass]] which also has the properties of [[safety glass]] when [[backboard shattering|accidentally shattered]]. It is usually [[rectangle|rectangular]] as used in [[NBA]], [[NCAA]] and international basketball. In recreational environments, a backboard may be [[oval]] or a [[Hand fan|fan]]-shape, particularly in non-professional games.

The top of the hoop is {{convert|10|ft|cm|0}} above the ground. Regulation backboards are {{convert|72|in|cm|0}} wide by {{convert|42|in|cm}} tall. All basketball rims (hoops) are {{convert|18|in|cm}} in diameter. The inner rectangle on the backboard is {{convert|24|in|cm}} wide by {{convert|18|in|cm}} tall.<ref>http://www.nba.com/analysis/rules_1.html Oct 17 2006 4:32AM</ref>

In professional and most higher college settings, the backboard is part of a portable stanchion that can be moved out of the way in other sports, though in most high schools and examples such as [[Stanford University]]'s [[Maples Pavilion]], backboards are mounted as part of a suspended system using ceiling joists to support the goal and allow them to be put out of the way in the ceiling when not in use.

The first glass backboard was used by the [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball]] team at the [[Men's Gymnasium (Indiana University)|Men's Gymnasium]] at [[Indiana University Bloomington|Indiana University]].<ref name="Hiner">{{cite book|last=Hiner|first=Jason|title=Indiana University Basketball Encyclopedia|year=2005|publisher=Sports Publishing|location=United States|isbn=1-58261-655-8|pages=447}}</ref> After the first few games at their new facility in 1917, spectators complained that they could not see the game because of opaque wooden backboards. As a result the Nurre Mirror Plate Company in [[Bloomington, Indiana|Bloomington]] was employed to create new backboards that contained {{convert|1+1/2|in|cm|-thick|adj=mid}} plate glass so that fans could see games without an obstructed view. It was the first facility in the country to use glass backboards.<ref name="Hiner"/>

Professional glass backboards used to break from {{convert|625|lbs|kg}} of force or more. Modern professional and higher-level college play backboards do not have the glass absorbing any weight to avoid breaking.<ref>{{Citation|last=rockboy1138|title=Sports Science puts NBA backboards to the test!|date=2009-12-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1946yBnxl0 |accessdate=2017-07-06}}</ref>

