[[Image:Cricket delivery lengths en.svg|thumb|right|325px|Lengths of balls showing name & bounce height. The good length is the middle path, indicated in red]] [[File:Length (cricket).svg|thumb|right|325px|A good length ball pitches in the bright green area of the pitch]] A '''good length ball''' is a type of [[Delivery (cricket)|delivery]] in [[cricket]] that pitches at a distance from the [[Batting (cricket)|batsman]] that makes it difficult to score [[Run (cricket)|runs]]. Furthermore, such a delivery is difficult for the batsman to judge whether to play on the [[Back foot contact|back-foot]] or on the [[Front foot contact|front-foot]]. However, the distance from the batsman which is the ideal good length varies depending on how high and fast the ball bounces on a particular pitch. The pace of the bowler is also a factor, as faster bowlers will aim to pitch the ball further away from the batsman.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/skills/4177344.stm| title = Bowling line and length | publisher = BBC| accessdate = 3 May 2011| date=6 September 2005}}</ref>
